Socionext (6526) | Japan
Socionext (6526.T)FromToPrice Target¥2,200¥2,600FY3/26e OP¥16.2bn¥18.0bnFY3/27e OP¥26.2bn¥26.5bn
We see longer- term growth potential for Socionext, but also risk as mass production from new business deals dampens gross margins (near term) and as competition heats up (longer term).

Remain EW on Socionext, but with slightly cautious bias: The stock price has been climbing, on expectations of a cyclical earnings recovery and for its longer- term growth potential. We also believe that last year's design win in server CPUs with a CSP in North America could unlock growth for Socionext in the data center field.

Near term, though, new products being mass produced (which are expected to drive earnings recovery in 2025- 26) will carry low gross margins, and yields especially in the early stages of mass production will likely be a source of uncertainty. We also see risk of tighter competition over the medium/long term, and not just with existing major design houses, but also with local design houses targeting Chinese customers, as well as with Arm Holdings (covered by our European semiconductors analyst Lee Simpson), which has shown ambition in designing ASICs for data centers (Arm Holdings plc: Investment Phase Signals Future Value Potential (31 Jul 2025)). While we maintain our EW rating on Socionext, we have a slightly cautious bias, believing current market expectations to be somewhat overheated.
Our PT values the stock at 22x our FY3/27e EPS: Based on our outlook for earnings recovery in 2025- 26, we bump up our target P/E from 19x to 22x (the historical average multiple).

Fine- tuning our earnings forecasts; where we differ vs. consensus: The primary change in our model is our USDJPY assumption from ¥14.0 to ¥14.5. When accounting for the differences in FX assumptions, our FY3/26 OP forecast is actually below company guidance marginally. Our OP forecasts for both FY3/26 and FY3/27 are lower than consensus, though by only \(\sim 3\%\) .

Sep- Q earnings preview: Our Sep- Q forecasts, based on a USDJPY rate of ¥14.7 (¥14.5 from Sep onward), have sales at ¥45.3bn (- 2% YoY, +31% QoQ), gross margin of 51.0% (- 7.3ppt QoQ), product gross margin of 38.7% (- 5.7ppt QoQ), and OP at ¥2.5bn. Our OP forecast is lower than the IFIS consensus of ¥3.1bn.

What to watch in Socionext's Sept Q results: (1) any changes in the company's outlook for a 2H recovery in sales, caused by the ramp- up of ADAS products for a Chinese automotive OEM; (2) new design wins in 1H (Socionext's FY3/26 target is for \(\sim\) 360bn in new business, flat YoY; based on ¥120/\\$ assumption).

As well as raising our earnings forecasts, mainly reflecting a revised \(\yen 123,456\) tax assumption, we have raised our target multiple, and thus lift our price target from \(\yen 2,200\) to \(\yen 2,600\) . However, we maintain our Equal- weight rating and have a relatively guarded stance.

Our PT is based on P/E of \(22x\) (in line with the stock's past average) applied to our estimate for EPS in FY3/27, when server CPUs for a North American cloud service provider are due to go into mass production.

Our previous PT applied a \(10\%\) discount to the multiples of rival Asian ASIC design houses (Alchip and Global Unchip, covered by our Greater China Semiconductor analyst Charlie Chan), or P/E of \(19x\) , to our FY3/27 EPS estimate. However, P/E multiples have expanded sharply for both Alchip and GUC, and we think they no longer present an appropriate point of reference for Socionext. We therefore base our new PT on the stock's own historical average multiple, or \(22x\) , still applied to our FY3/27 EPS.

The FCF ratio implied by our PT (based on our FY3/27 FCF forecast) is a low \(1.5\%\) , but we think the market would be satisfied with a relatively high valuation from this perspective, given the outlook for continuing profit growth in 2026- 27 with mass production of server CPUs for N. American CSPs, and Socionext's good positioning among advanced ASIC design houses on the global stage as well.
Exhibit 1: Socionext: 1-year forward P/E (consensus EPS basis)
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

The share price fell continuously after the company's announcement of a downward revision to earnings guidance for FY3/25 in January 2025 (mainly on the grounds of a slowdown in the outlook for demand for products for Chinese communications equipment and prolonged inventory correction at customers). However, it has ticked upward since the results release in April 2025 on expectations of bottoming and recovery in earnings, and volume ramp of ADAS products for a Chinese automobile OEM in 2H25 and server CPUs for the N. American CSP in 2H26.
Exhibit 15: Socionext: Consolidated statement of financial position
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research. \(\epsilon =\) Morgan Stanley Research estimates
as including expectations of earnings contributions from server CPUs for the North American CSP going into mass production from around 2H26, and the outlook for new design- wins.

Regarding server CPUs for the N. American CSP, Socionext management has indicated the prospect of life- time value of US \(\) 500\(mn - 1bn. Taking the mid - point of this guidance range, we assume the related life - time value at US\) \ \(750mn\) , \(\sim\) 150mn in non- recurring engineering (NRE) sales, and annual product sales of US \(\) 200mn\(over a three - year mass production period ( \sim\) 29bn @\) \ \(145 / \S\) ).

That said, the width of the management guidance range may also present ample scope for the numbers to be much higher than our forecasts. Considering such uncertainties, and the high volatility of the share price, we do not have sufficient conviction to downgrade to UW despite the share price currently being below our PT.

We fine- tune our forecasts based on June- Q results. The primary change in our models is our USDJPY assumption from \(\) 140\(to\) \ \(145\) . When accounting for the differences in FX assumptions, our FY3/26 OP forecast is actually below company guidance marginally. Our OP forecasts for both FY3/26 and FY3/27 are lower than consensus, though by only \(\sim 3\%\) .
Exhibit 4: Socionext: Earnings forecast
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research. Ce = Company estimates, e = Morgan Stanley Research estimates.

FY3/26: We expect earnings to recover after bottoming back in the June- Q. Driving the recovery at the top line are products for Chinese communication equipment (had been seeing shipment delays) as well as ADAS products for a Chinese automotive OEM. Both product categories have gross margins that are lower than the company- wide target for \(40\%\) . As such, even though sales are set to recover, we expect gross margins to slip and OP to recover at only a gradual pace. Looking into the past, Socionext saw product gross margins decline back in FY3/23 when sales of leading- edge 7nm products climbed.
Exhibit 5: Socionext: Sales by application
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research. \(\epsilon =\) Morgan Stanley Research estimates.
Exhibit 6: Socionext: Quarterly sales and product gross margin
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research. \(\epsilon =\) Morgan Stanley Research estimates.
Exhibit 7: Socionext: 3-7nm product sales and product gross margin
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

FY3/27: Although Socionext's 5G network contract in China will reach end- of- life in FY3/27, the start of mass production for server CPUs for a North American CSP should drive significant sales growth in the network and data center segments. In the automotive segment, we also expect sales growth to carry on, supported by full- year contributions from ADAS products for Chinese OEMs and ramp- up of products for a North American OEM.

That said, one risk is that ADAS products for Chinese OEMs, which we expect to ramp up strongly within FY3/26, could see significant volatility depending on sell- through trends for new products on the customer side.
Additionally, product gross margins are likely to continue declining as mass production of 3nm server CPUs for North American CSPs ramps up.

We believe Socionext has a significant growth opportunity in advanced ASIC in the medium to long run. In 2025, 7nm ADAS chip for a Chinese OEM will ramp, and in 2026, 3nm server CPU for a US CSP will ramp.

In the near- term, however, profit recovery is likely to be muted as new products have low gross margin. In the medium to long run, in addition to global major ASIC vendors, competition with Chinese design houses over Chinese customers, competition with Arm over data center projects may intensify.
